    "instruction": "For metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv: 1) Compute the global 95th percentile (P95) of the 'value' column grouped by (cmdb_id, KPI_name) where KPI_name is kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, and log_name for log.csv. Do NOT filter by time; use the full series. 2) Store the full group-by results in kernel variables (e.g., metric_p95, trace_p95, log_p95). 3) Return a compact summary for each file containing: a) the number of distinct (cmdb_id, KPI) groups, and b) the top 20 groups sorted by descending P95 with columns (cmdb_id, KPI_name, p95). Limit each list to at most 20 rows. Do not print full time series. Return results as a dictionary keyed by filename (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv) with fields 'group_count' and 'top_p95' (list of rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed per-(cmdb_id,KPI) global P95s and then filtered data to the incident window (2022-03-21 08:30–09:00 UTC+8). Compact anomaly aggregates show multiple metric anomalies concentrated on node-1 I/O KPIs (system.io.r_s, system.io.w_s, system.io.rkb_s, system.io.avg_q_sz, system.io.util, system.load.1) with earliest anomaly timestamps around 1647823000–1647824000. Trace anomalies cluster around checkoutservice ↔ shippingservice and cartservice (earliest anomaly timestamps around 1647823000). Logs show increased log.row_count (no error_count) for several services around the same timestamps. Together these indicate a likely node-level resource problem (node-1 I/O) starting near timestamp 1647823000 that caused increased service latencies across multiple services. To confirm this hypothesis and determine the exact root cause occurrence time and fault duration, we need to identify consecutive anomaly runs (faults) for node-level KPIs and their first occurrence times. If node-1 shows the earliest and most severe consecutive faults, it will likely be the root cause level/component and the first anomaly timestamp of that run will be the root cause occurrence time. \n\nI will now request a focused detection of consecutive anomaly runs for node-level metrics (cmdb_id starting with 'node-') in the incident window so we can extract precise run start times, durations, and severity for localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "In metric_window (the filtered metric data for the incident window) find all groups where cmdb_id starts with 'node-'. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group, detect consecutive runs of timestamps where value > p95 (use p95 from metric_p95). A 'consecutive' run means consecutive sampled points in the window (timestamps are per-minute). For each run with length >= 2, compute and store: cmdb_id, KPI_name, run_start_ts (first timestamp of run), run_end_ts (last timestamp of run), run_length (number of points), earliest_anomaly_ts (same as run_start_ts), max_value_in_run, p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_run - p95)/p95 (null if p95==0). Save the full table as node_fault_runs in kernel. Return a compact list of up to top 20 runs sorted by severity_ratio desc, showing the columns above. Also return the count of distinct node-level groups examined and the count of runs found."}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor detected 26 consecutive anomaly runs for node-level KPIs in the incident window and reported the top runs. The most severe run is node-1 | system.io.r_s with run_start_ts = 1647822840 and run_length = 2 (severity_ratio 6.38). Additional node-1 runs include high system.io.rkb_s and later system.load and cpu runs (some starting ~1647823980 and ~1647824220). Trace and log anomaly aggregates from earlier steps show elevated latencies and increased log.row_count for multiple services with earliest anomalies around 1647823000. The node-1 I/O run_start at 1647822840 precedes many service-level anomalies (~1647823000), which suggests node-1 I/O degradation is the likely root-level problem that caused downstream service latency and increased log counts. However, to localize the exact root cause component and precise occurrence datetime we must confirm that: 1) node-1 faults start earlier than other faults, 2) multiple downstream services exhibit anomalies after node-1's first anomalous timestamp, and 3) traces indicate propagation consistent with node-level I/O impact rather than a single service failure. \n\nNext we should correlate timing: retrieve trace and log anomaly groups whose earliest_anomaly_ts occur at or shortly after node-1's earliest anomalous timestamp (1647822840) to confirm temporal ordering and identify affected services. This will help finalize the root cause component, the precise first occurrence time, and reason.",
